	<td class="alt2" valign="top">
	
	<!-- message -->
	<p>It depends.  <br />
<br />
In my prefered group with a bard pulling and a SK tanking, the mobs never look at me...  The bard will occlusion and slow the mob before it gets to camp, the SK will snare as soon as its in range (even ifits not snareable, its good agro), I slow as soon as its in range, and never get agro.<br />
<br />
In a typical group, if the tank pulls they will have enough agro for me to slow with only occasionaly getting agro.  I malo as soon as the mob is in range (on its way to camp) and slow as soon as the gem refreshes (usualy land slow before the assist call).<br />
<br />
If we have a dedicated puller (fd splitting or lull/pacify pulling) I know I will have agro at the beginning of the fight.  I stand where the MT is waiting for the mob (so he wont have to chase it).  I torpor myself at the end of the fight (while cannibalizing back whatever mana I used) and if things are moving along this means I have torpor on when the puller brings the next mob in.  I malo as soon as the mob is in range, and slow as soon as the gem refreshes.  Slow will usualy land just as the mob reaches camp -and I will take the first few hits while the mt attacks/taunts/whatever it is they do.  Once the mt has agro I move back a few steps, we kill it, rinse and repeat.<br />
<br />
In any case, the mob is slowed as soon as it reaches camp.  I use malo even at 65 to ensure that my slow lands on the first try.  I can tank a slowed PoP mob for a bit if I have to.  I cant keep a tank alive versus an unslowed PoP mob, much less a caster.<br />
<br />
If there are multiple mobs, I trust the crowd controll person to handle them.  If I am the cc person, I root the first one in range, and then try to land slow on the one we are fighting before the tank dies... if not, well.. I told them to pull singles  <img src="images/smilies/tongue.gif" border="0" alt="" title="stick out tongue" smilieid="6" /></p>
	
	
	
